The rand weakened to over R14/$ on Thursday morning as the dollar strengthened against most currencies following the US central bank&rsquo;s decision to raise interest rates by 25 basis points.Even though the US Federal Reserve&rsquo;s move was widely expected, it caused most stock exchanges to fall.All three of Wall Street&rsquo;s major indices closed down on Wednesday, with the S&amp;P 500 losing 0.81%. Hopes that the Down Jones Industrial index would break the 20,000 index point barrier for the first time were dashed by it falling 0.6% to 19793 points.London&rsquo;s FTSE 100 closed 0.28% lower ahead of the Bank of England&rsquo;s interest rate vote which will be announced at 2pm South African time. The UK&rsquo;s central bank is expected to announce no change to its 0.25% rate and &pound;435bn quantitative easing programme.Hong Kong&rsquo;s Hang Seng was down 1.69%, but Tokyo&rsquo;s manufacturers benefited from a weaker yen. The Topix gained 0.57% and the Nikkei 225 0.31%.The JSE&rsquo;s all share index closed 0.24% lower on Wednesday, dragged down by Steinhoff&rsquo;s 7.11% drop to R70.58 and Shoprite&rsquo;s 7.17% drop to R178.97 following a proposal by major shareholders Christo Wiese and the Public Investment Corporation to merge their African retailers.The deal would see Frankfurt- and Johannesburg-listed Steinhoff sell Pep, Ackermans and other South African retailers to Shoprite in exchange for shares, making it a major shareholder in the grocery chain.Statistics SA is scheduled to release November&rsquo;s producer price index at 11.30am on Thursday. SA&rsquo;s factory and farm gate inflation is expected to have accelerated to 6.8% from October&rsquo;s 6.6%.